			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The advantage of putting hashes into the manifest file is that it would allow the browser to implement a share-by-hash scheme for transparent cross-origin sharing of file content (see http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/wiki/ShareByHash).

If the browser were to rely on the hash stored in the pexe it would increase the number of round trips compared with NMF-based share-by-hash:

 * For a cache hit, the browser has to fetch the NMF + a header from the pexe: 2 round trips.  (If the hash is in the NMF, just 1 round trip is needed.)

 * For a cache miss, the browser has to fetch the NMF + a header from the pexe + then the whole pexe: at least 3 round trips.  (If the hash is in the NMF, just 2 round trips are needed for the NMF and the pexe each.)</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-09-18T21:40:50.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-09-18T21:40:50.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 1 by mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=2992#c1" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/2992/comments/full/1" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>